07922nam a22008415i 9780776624303DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20162016xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807766243037 a10.1515/97807766243032doi  a(DE-B1597)668173  a(OCoLC)959691683  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aLAW0960002bisacsh04a347.0028522300aeAccess to Justice /ced. by Karim Benyekhlef, Fabien Gélinas, Jacquelyn Burkell, Jane Bailey. 1aOttawa : bUniversity of Ottawa Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (460 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLaw, Technology and Media00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tPART I JUSTICE VALUES AND DIGITALIZATION -- tINTRODUCTION Fundamental Values in a Technologized Age of Efficiency -- tCHAPTER I Cyberjustice and International Development: Reducing the Gap Between Promises and Accomplishments -- tCHAPTER II Evaluating e-Justice: The Design of an Assessment Framework for e-Justice Systems -- tCHAPTER III The Role of Courts in Assisting Individuals in Realizing Their s. 2(b) Right to Information about Court Proceedings -- tCHAPTER IV Privacy v. Transparency: How Remote Access to Court Records Forces Us to Re-examine Our Fundamental Values -- tPART II COURTROOM INTERACTIONS AND SELF-EMPOWERMENT -- tIntroduction: Troubling the Technological Imperative: Views on Responsible Implementation of Court Technologies -- tCHAPTER V ATJ Technology Principles: Access to and Delivery of Justice -- tCHAPTER VI Empowerment, Technology, and Family Law -- tCHAPTER VII The Case for Courtroom Technology Competence as an Ethical Duty for Litigators -- tCHAPTER VIII Tablets in the Jury Room: Enhancing Performance while Undermining Fairness? -- tPART III TOWARD NEW PROCEDURAL MODELS? -- tIntroduction: Continuity and Technological Change in Justice Delivery -- tCHAPTER IX The Old...and the New? Elements for a General Theory of Institutional Change: The Case of Paperless Justice -- tCHAPTER X Cyberjustice and Ethical Perspectives of Procedural Law -- tCHAPTER XI Three Trade-Offs to Efficient Dispute Resolution -- tCHAPTER XII The Electronic Process in the Brazilian Judicial System: Much More Than an Option; It Is a Solution -- tCHAPTER XIII Access to Justice and Technology: Transforming the Face of Cross- Border Civil Litigation and Adjudication in the EU -- tPOSTSCRIPT eAccess to Justice - Brief Observations -- tBibliography -- tContributors0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aPart I of this work focuses on the ways in which digitization projects can affect fundamental justice principles. It examines claims that technology will improve justice system efficiency and offers a model for evaluating e-justice systems that incorporates a broader range of justice system values. The emphasis is on the complicated relationship between privacy and transparency in making court records and decisions available online. Part II examines the implementation of technologies in the justice system and the challenges it comes with, focusing on four different technologies: online court information systems, e-filing, videoconferencing, and tablets for presentation and review of evidence by jurors. The authors share a measuring enthusiasm for technological advances in the courts, emphasizing that these technologies should be implemented with care to ensure the best possible outcome for access to a fair and effective justice system. Finally, Part III adopts the standpoints of sociology, political theory and legal theory to explore the complex web of values, norms, and practices that support our systems of justice, the reasons for their well-established resistance to change, and the avenues and prospects of eAccess. The chapters in this section provide a unique and valuable framework for thinking with the required sophistication about legal change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConduct of court proceedingsxTechnological innovations. 0aCourt administrationxAutomation. 0aJustice, Administration ofxAutomation. 7aLAW / Media & the Law.2bisacsh1 aBailey, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBailey, Jane, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBalbino, Katia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeauchard, Renaud, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenyekhlef, Karim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenyekhlef, Karim, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBurkell, Jacquelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurkell, Jacquelyn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCamion, Clément, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCanivet, Guy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerreira, Carvalho, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGélinas, Fabien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGélinas, Fabien, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHorowitz, Donald J, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKramer, Xandra E, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLupo, Giampiero, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacLennan, Sherry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoreau, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r